And even then it was mild anxiety compared to what I’ve been experiencing this past week. And now I’m pretty calm, thankfully.

This morning was a really good sign though. This past week I have woken up and been immediately bombarded with anxiety as soon as I open my eyes, but this morning I only started getting anxious when I was becoming fully awake.
To say the least though, this past week has been the LONGEST week of my entire life.
I’m not discouraging it’s usage, and obviously everyone reacts differently to different drugs. Just be careful. And if you’re going through the same thing, you’re not alone and it’ll be over soon

I would just really be careful taking this medication if your doctor suggests it, because I’ve heard a lot of similar stories to mine. I also read an article earlier today where they went back and were like withdrawal from this drug may be more intense than originally thought

Today I woke up less anxious (yay) but I think I’m experiencing a new symptom which is dizziness. I randomly got dizzy sitting down looking at my phone.(not by quickly sitting or standing, I was already still)

I bought delta 8 gummies for anxiety because my anxiety was SO HIGH I couldn’t do anything. Like I would just sit on my couch unable to move. They seem to be helping with my anxiety, and yesterday I took some and it was the first day I’ve had this week without feeling anxious

I forgot to mention that the first week after I went off of it I started having problems sleeping - being able to fall asleep and not being able to stay asleep. On top of vivid dreams. Both of these symptoms seem to be getting better.
I’ve also started experiencing diarrhea this past week. Which is also a listed symptom of Cymbalta withdrawal, as well as a symptom of having anxiety.
Then it progressed throughout the week to where I have been incredibly anxious all day every day for the past few days. I’ve barely been eating because I can’t eat when I’m anxious.

Crying randomly graduated into full blown anxiety this past week (a day or two after New Years). Like debilitating, overwhelming anxiety. It started out just random. I’d experience a little anxiety and then it would ease off
When I started crying and started spiraling more than usual it kind of clicked that I might be going through withdrawal from Cymbalta (which again I didn’t really experience going off celexa.)

I hope I’m not confusing y’all with my over explanation of a time line. I have ADHD so sometimes time is weird in my brain. It actually feels like I’ve been off Cymbalta for a lot longer than I have. I went off of it Dec 7 2021
Bc I thought the brain zaps and irritability would be the worst of my withdrawal, and Christmas I wasn’t experiencing ANY symptoms until I gradually just started crying for no reason.

That was the last week of December into January (so the week after Christmas and of New Years this year) Thankfully I actually felt decent on Christmas and, which is why I wasn’t thinking of withdrawal when I started experiencing my worst symptoms
And that gradually graduated into just random bouts of crying. Like without feeling anxious in my body or having my thoughts spiral. I would just cry, randomly, for no Discernible reason.

The second week the brain zaps started going away but I started experiencing paranoia. Not exactly anxiety but being jumpy and on edge. Also my neck and shoulder muscles would get incredibly tense. Irritability also started happening
The first week of stopping taking it completely, I experienced bad brain zaps when I woke up and when I was getting into bed
I was on celexa for almost a decade and did not experience near as bad withdrawal symptoms as I am right now after going off Cymbalta
For anyone taking Cymbalta or thinking about going off of it - I tapered off as safely as possible and what was recommended by my doctor and I have had debilitating withdrawal symptoms

Currently on Strattera for ADHD and a low dose of Cymbalta for anxiety ✌️ and that’s okay ❤️

Mental health Medication isn’t something you don’t actually need. Some of us actually need it. Your brain is an organ, and sometimes shit goes awry and it doesn’t release or do what it’s supposed to. And that’s okay

And medicine is what keeps me on track. So I can paint and write and shower and do all the things that I enjoy doing that ALSO help alleviate my symptoms, but needing and taking that step one (meds) to get to that step 2 (enjoying life and being less stressed) isn’t a failure

I made myself get up and take my medicine. Within 20 minutes I was able to leave bed, stop crying, my anxiety dissipated, and I was able to shower and get dressed. Yes, therapy has helped me and mindful thinking/activities but sometimes my brain just goes 404 ERROR

For the people asking why people take medication for mental health when you can “just get over it”: I was in bed awake for an hour or more and hadn’t taken my medicine yet. I let myself spiral in my head and started having an anxiety attack and felt super depressed.
